<AbstractNarration>0545606&lt;br/&gt;Holt&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;The overriding-objective of this project is to use Earthscope data to&lt;br/&gt;determine a high-precision, high resolution, four-dimensional image of&lt;br/&gt;crustal deformation for the North America continent on time-scales of days&lt;br/&gt;to decades, and spatial-scales of kilometers to thousands of kilometers.&lt;br/&gt;We are pursuing this goal by analyzing continuous GPS data from Earthscope's&lt;br/&gt;Plate Boundary Observatory (PBO) facility, and by expanding upon past&lt;br/&gt;experience in the analysis and modeling of plate boundary-scale crustal&lt;br/&gt;deformations to better account for time-dependence of crustal motions.   The&lt;br/&gt;fundamental objective of developing methods to realize four-dimensional&lt;br/&gt;solutions of the velocity gradient tensor field will be achieved prior to&lt;br/&gt;the full implementation of Earthscope.  It is a primary goal to develop a&lt;br/&gt;tool that the community can use for future analysis of Earthscope data as&lt;br/&gt;the project matures.&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
